            "title": "Rashid Khan Returns to Afghanistan ODI Squad for South Africa Series",
            "image": "https://cricketchampion.co.in/webroot/img/news/693941017_news.webp",
            "description": "Afghanistan’s star legspinner, Rashid Khan, is set to make his return to One-Day Internationals for the first time since last year’s World Cup...",
            "content": [
                "<p>Afghanistan&rsquo;s star legspinner, Rashid Khan, is set to make his return to One-Day Internationals for the first time since last year&rsquo;s World Cup. Rashid has been named in a 17-member squad for Afghanistan&rsquo;s upcoming three-match ODI series against South Africa in the UAE, marking his long-awaited comeback after months of injury rehabilitation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The return of Rashid Khan is a significant boost for Afghanistan&rsquo;s bowling attack, especially as the team will continue to miss the services of mystery spinner Mujeeb Ur Rahman. Mujeeb is still recovering from a sprained index finger on his right hand, and as a result, has been ruled out of the series. The team has also opted to leave out wristspinner Noor Ahmad, with chief selector Ahmad Shah Sulimankhil confirming that offspinner AM Ghazanfar, who made his ODI debut earlier this year, will cover for Mujeeb in the South Africa series.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rashid&rsquo;s return follows a lengthy absence from international cricket after undergoing back surgery last year, which sidelined him for four months. During that period, he missed multiple assignments, including series against the UAE, India, Sri Lanka, and Ireland. He was also forced to withdraw from the Big Bash League (BBL), Pakistan Super League (PSL), and the SA20, before making his return in Afghanistan&rsquo;s T20I series against Ireland in March.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since his surgery, Rashid has focused on T20 formats, playing in several high-profile leagues, including the Indian Premier League (IPL), the T20 World Cup, the Major League Cricket (MLC), and the Hundred. However, he struggled with back and hamstring injuries, which further delayed his full recovery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Afghanistan&#39;s ODI squad for the series against South Africa also includes uncapped medium-pace bowler Bilal Sami, along with top-order batters Darwish Rasooli and Abdul Malik. While Rasooli has represented Afghanistan in seven T20Is, Malik has played two Tests but is yet to feature in ODIs. Sami has yet to make his international debut in any format. Malik&rsquo;s inclusion serves as cover for opening batter Ibrahim Zadran, who is nursing an ankle sprain that has kept him out of both the ongoing Test against New Zealand and the upcoming ODIs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The three-match ODI series against South Africa will take place in Sharjah, starting on September 18. This series will be the first-ever bilateral ODI encounter between Afghanistan and South Africa, with the two teams having previously met only in the 2019 and 2023 World Cups.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The series also serves as crucial preparation for Afghanistan ahead of the 2024 Champions Trophy, for which the team qualified for the first time after finishing sixth in the league stage of the 2023 World Cup.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Afghanistan Squad for South Africa ODIs:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hashmatullah Shahidi (capt), Rahmat Shah, Rahmanullah Gurbaz, Ikram Alikhil, Abdul Malik, Riaz Hassan, Darwish Rasooli, Azmatullah Omarzai, Mohammad Nabi, Gulbadin Naib, Rashid Khan, Nangeyalia Kharote, AM Ghazanfar, Fazalhaq Farooqi, Bilal Sami, Naveed Zadran, Fareed Ahmad.</p>\r\n"
            ],
