            "title": "Glenn Maxwell Powers Melbourne Stars to BBL Finals with Explosive Knock",
            "image": "https://cricketchampion.co.in/webroot/img/news/1293479879_news.webp",
            "description": "Glenn Maxwell may not be heading to Sri Lanka with the Australian Test squad, but he’s ensured a thrilling end...",
            "content": [
                "<p>Glenn Maxwell may not be heading to Sri Lanka with the Australian Test squad, but he&rsquo;s ensured a thrilling end to the Melbourne Stars&#39; regular season, guiding them into the Big Bash League (BBL) finals. Maxwell&rsquo;s blistering 76 not out off 32 balls helped the Stars to a dominant victory over Hobart Hurricanes at the MCG, securing a fourth-place finish and a spot in the finals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Stars needed a win to leapfrog Perth Scorchers into the top four, and they delivered with ease, defeating a Hurricanes side with little to play for after already securing the top spot in the standings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maxwell, in scintillating form following his remarkable 90 in the previous game against the Renegades, got the crowd on their feet early, blasting a six on his fourth delivery. His partnership with Beau Webster, who also scored a half-century, pushed the Stars past 200, a total that would prove too much for the Hurricanes. Maxwell added three more sixes, including one off quick Cameron Gannon, as the Stars finished with 204/4 from their 20 overs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite struggling with the bat earlier in the season, the Stars showed immense improvement, particularly at the top of the order. Openers Sam Harper and Thomas Rogers provided a solid platform, with Harper&rsquo;s four early boundaries setting the tone. However, both were dismissed during the powerplay, with Rogers falling to Nathan Ellis&rsquo; clever change of pace and Harper being trapped lbw by spinner Nikhil Chaudhary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Marcus Stoinis, who had been inconsistent throughout the season, tried to maintain the momentum with a quick-fire 32 from 19 balls, but once he fell, it was Maxwell who took over. His fast-paced innings, full of powerful hitting, ensured the Stars set a challenging target.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hobart&rsquo;s bowling attack, including a mix of experimental selections and injuries, struggled to contain Maxwell&rsquo;s onslaught. Riley Meredith was absent, and Nathan Ellis bowled only one over due to a sore groin. Chris Jordan, making his return from a back injury, also faced difficulties as Maxwell took control in the later stages. Despite some promising moments from debutant Marcus Bean and Gannon, both bowlers found themselves on the receiving end of Maxwell&rsquo;s power.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Hurricanes&rsquo; chase got off to a flying start with Mitchell Owen, who struck a couple of big sixes early on and raced to 34 from just 10 balls. However, his momentum slowed, and he eventually holed out for 38. The Hurricanes&rsquo; slim hopes of chasing down the target were effectively ended when Steketee claimed key wickets, finishing with figures of 4/24 from just 3.3 overs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ellis top-scored for the Hurricanes with a rapid 40 at the end, but his dismissal to Maxwell sealed the Stars&#39; comprehensive victory. With this win, the Melbourne Stars secured a spot in the knockout final against Sydney Thunder at the Showgrounds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maxwell&rsquo;s stellar performance not only ensured the Stars&rsquo; progression to the finals for the first time since BBL 09 but also provided a welcome boost for the veteran, whose Test career now looks uncertain after being overlooked for the Sri Lanka tour. The Stars, having turned around a disappointing start to the season, will head into the finals with confidence after five consecutive wins.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Hurricanes, on the other hand, will play in the Qualifier against Sydney Sixers, after securing the top spot in the standings, but their performance in this match will be a concern heading into the business end of the competition.</p>\r\n"
            ],
