            "title": "Heather Knight Confident England Can Turn Ashes Series Around",
            "image": "https://cricketchampion.co.in/webroot/img/news/417159999_news.webp",
            "description": "Heather Knight remains optimistic that a shift in format and the introduction of fresh talent will give England...",
            "content": [
                "<p>Heather Knight remains optimistic that a shift in format and the introduction of fresh talent will give England the momentum needed to salvage the Ashes series, following a crushing 3-0 defeat in the One Day Internationals (ODIs).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After Australia&rsquo;s dominant ODI whitewash, England finds itself with no margin for error in the remaining multiformat Ashes series. With the team trailing 6-0, they must win all of the upcoming three T20Is and the day-night Test at the MCG to force a 6-6 draw. Even if the series is tied heading into the Test, Australia would only need a draw to retain the Ashes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&rsquo;ve got to keep believing, but we can&#39;t look too far ahead,&quot; Knight said. &quot;In the last Ashes series, we were 6-0 down and managed to turn things around. I think the change of format will be good for us, especially with T20 cricket being one of our strongest formats. A little reset should do us some good.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knight also emphasized the importance of focusing on one match at a time, as England did during the last Ashes series when they managed to build momentum after being down. The inclusion of fresh faces, such as Bess Heath, Dani Gibson, Freya Kemp, and Linsey Smith, for the upcoming T20Is, offers hope of rejuvenating the squad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both teams have something to prove in the T20I format. England&rsquo;s early exit from last year&#39;s T20 World Cup in the UAE, coupled with Australia&#39;s semi-final loss, adds an extra layer of intensity to the upcoming matches. Despite Australia&rsquo;s lack of T20I action since that tournament, Knight does not believe it gives the home side a major advantage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think they&#39;re a team that plays T20 cricket very well, as are we,&quot; Knight said. &quot;We&rsquo;ve had some excellent T20 performances recently, so the lack of recent matches for Australia may not be as significant as some might think.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The next challenge for England will be the pink-ball Test at the MCG, where Kate Cross will be crucial to their preparations. Knight confirmed that Cross, who has been recovering from a back injury, was close to being available for the final ODI but was ultimately held back to avoid further risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Kate felt she was close to playing, but we felt it was too much of a risk given her lack of recent cricket,&quot; Knight explained. &quot;Her injury can flare up at any time, so we&#39;re taking a cautious approach.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With just two days between the end of the ODIs and the first T20I at the SCG, and a four-day gap before the Test, switching between formats will be challenging for the players. However, Knight is confident that the squad is moving in the right direction, with special preparation planned for the Test match players, including Tammy Beaumont and Ryana MacDonald-Gay, who will be attending a camp to prepare specifically for the four-day encounter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australia is expected to announce its Test squad on Monday, as the series heads into a crucial phase.</p>\r\n"
            ],
